Here’s a basic example of Flexbox in action:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}
```

Example Grid layout:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 20px;
}
```

Now, `useEffect` is another powerful hook. It's like a combination of `componentDidMount`, `componentDidUpdate`, and `componentWillUnmount` in class components. You can use it for side effects like fetching data or setting up subscriptions:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Component mounted or updated');
}, [dependencies]);
```

Hooks also promote better separation of concerns. You can extract logic into custom hooks — functions that start with `use` — to make your code modular and reusable:

```jsx
function useCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const increment = () => setCount((c) => c + 1);
  return { count, increment };
}
```

```jsx
const [darkMode, setDarkMode] = useState(false);

useEffect(() => {
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark', darkMode);
}, [darkMode]);
```

